There is much to say about the summer of Taylor that is pertinent to techno=
logy and the Internet: start with the desire for communal in-person experie=
nces driven not only by the pandemic, but also the general fracturing of cu=
lture inherent in a media landscape where personalized content delivered di=
rectly to your personal device is the norm. Then there is the way in which =
social media acts as a FOMO generator: being able to access every moment of=
 every show on social media doesn=E2=80=99t decrease the value of attending=
 the show, but rather increases the desire to obtain a scarce number of tic=
kets to see the spectacle in person. And, it must be said, there is the exc=
ellence at play: not only does Swift have an incredible catalog of popular =
songs, the show itself spares no expense =E2=80=94 or exertion on Swift=E2=
=80=99s part =E2=80=94 to give the fans exactly what they were hoping for.

The Tyson-Paul fight wasn=E2=80=99t exactly analogous to Swift=E2=80=99s Er=
as Tour, although there was a live audience of 70,000 at AT&T Stadium in Da=
llas; what there was in common was the expectation and delivery of a shared=
 experience amplified by social media, not fractured by it. And, in that re=
gard, it delivered; to put that 65 million figure in perspective:

* 67 million people watched the Trump-Harris presidential debate, although =
the latter is a U.S.-only figure, and does not include online streaming pla=
tforms. 73 million watched the Trump-Biden debate this summer, and 84 milli=
on watched the first debate between Trump and Hillary Clinton.
* 84 million people watched the Cheers finale, 76 million people watched th=
e Seinfeld finale, and 53 million people watched the Friends finale.
* 124 million people watched the 2024 Super Bowl; to loop streaming into th=
is discussion, 23 million people watched the NFL playoff game that was on P=
eacock.

Again, that Netflix streaming number is global; I watched it in Taiwan, and=
 didn=E2=80=99t have any streaming issues, probably because I didn=E2=80=99=
t have much competition for the stream. The challenge for Netflix is that w=
hile most of its content is on-demand, streaming a live event means everyon=
e wants the same content at the same time, which isn=E2=80=99t pre-loaded o=
nto the servers Netflix co-locates with most of the world=E2=80=99s ISPs. I=
t=E2=80=99s interesting to note that linear television, which is so often v=
iewed as an inferior user experience because it is not on-demand, is in fac=
t perfectly suited to this sort of massive one-to-many broadcast (the probl=
em is that this is the format via which everything is delivered, even if it=
=E2=80=99s not live and watched by everyone everywhere all at once).

Given that inherent complexity, I have to assume that Netflix viewed this e=
vent as an unbridled success, even with the hiccups it encountered (and, fo=
r what it=E2=80=99s worth, the streaming service appeared to have solved th=
e streaming issues by the time the main event rolled around). Those viewers=
hip numbers I posted above are hallowed grounds in terms of television broa=
dcasts; they look even better if you place them in the context of 2023=E2=
=80=99s most viewed broadcasts. Sportico posted this arresting graphic ( ht=
tps://www.sportico.com/business/media/2024/nfl-posts-93-of-top-100-tv-broad=
casts-2023-1234761753/ ) earlier this year:

The most-watched TV broadcasts in the U.S. in 2003 ( https://www.sportico.c=
om/business/media/2024/nfl-posts-93-of-top-100-tv-broadcasts-2023-123476175=
3/ )

