AP1ecihu43idgTtpXF9D5cm78ZobE2tUixtT_gIFJKQP1OXZRMWitfaUlBeycAa_xN0n5oqgOZn=
w2iw ) :

At this point, I think my overall conclusion on this deal is clear: a singl=
e-day NFL package is, unlike most of the other NFL deals, one that is prima=
rily useful for customer acquisition, not churn mitigation. That, meanwhile=
, is exactly what Netflix wants. Moreover, the NFL reaches audiences that N=
etflix wants to reach more effectively than anything else; the challenge/op=
portunity for Netflix will be to retain that audience for the long run, whi=
le monetizing them via ads, which is to say the challenge/opportunity prese=
nted by the NFL is perfectly aligned with Netflix=E2=80=99s corporate objec=
tives.

To zoom out on this point, I noted in a 2018 Update ( https://stratechery.c=
om/2018/netflix-earnings-netflixs-rising-cac-content-and-marketing/?access_=
token=3DeyJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiIsImtpZCI6InN0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LnBhc3Nwb3J0Lm9ubGluZSI=
sInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9.eyJhdWQiOiJzdHJhdGVjaGVyeS5wYXNzcG9ydC5vbmxpbmUiLCJhenAiO=
iJIS0xjUzREd1Nod1AyWURLYmZQV00xIiwiZW50Ijp7InVyaSI6WyJodHRwczovL3N0cmF0ZWNo=
ZXJ5LmNvbS8yMDE4L25ldGZsaXgtZWFybmluZ3MtbmV0ZmxpeHMtcmlzaW5nLWNhYy1jb250ZW5=
0LWFuZC1tYXJrZXRpbmcvIl19LCJleHAiOjE3MzQ2MTMyMDYsImlhdCI6MTczMjAyMTIwNiwiaX=
NzIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly9hcGkucGFzc3BvcnQub25saW5lL29hdXRoIiwic2NvcGUiOiJmZWVkOnJlY=
WQgYXJ0aWNsZTpyZWFkIGFzc2V0OnJlYWQgY2F0ZWdvcnk6cmVhZCBlbnRpdGxlbWVudHMiLCJz=
dWIiOiJSc2V1WUU4amdIZVBwV0pmMWZBYjRDIiwidXNlIjoiYWNjZXNzIn0.jqeHj-Xoe7zADMB=
rCiTRMK-j4D3XRSX34J95XdfS7pLTXWIxUM1VECsslXP_ecaAU4YQ5uDGikCB_gEftwooQUcUGB=
VCwkX-old3kAQsFKbBHvYFPREEhUWGh89OiueDQkHFHxNLeT3Z81VjCD6X9ptvyqbm5r9fu06f-=
lsQcOr-p2g730XMhRmknT81IiLVVWnEnZeFheVPET-7sR1tC6LczpmJWE02Bk6X0MtiCVRHE-Cg=
zjnRzn9xUqBAmqmDnBugp4P75rPy0paFL6SjW1jolr535vGExjfK_KH_QAdO0X_HxF0WncmtFZZ=
JfmtAAAzdHJoE8i7pM57N3Hk3oA ) that one of the challenges in accounting for =
Netflix=E2=80=99s costs is that some portion of its content spend was actua=
lly marketing spend, in that content drove customer acquisition. In the ide=
alized version of Netflix, which I held at the time, spending on evergreen =
content actually increased Netflix=E2=80=99s marginal attractiveness to the=
 marginal customer, who could not only watch the latest Netflix shows but a=
ll of the ones they missed.

In truth, that was probably over-stated; what I think this event strategy d=
emonstrates is that customer acquisition content is fundamentally different=
 from churn mitigraion content, and Netflix is leaning into that distinctio=
n. The vast majority of its shows are designed to be delivered on that same=
 Netflix infrastructure that was built to deliver whatever a customer wants=
 whenever they want it, on-demand and individualized; this boxing match, th=
ough, and the NFL games, are not evergreen content, and they=E2=80=99re not=
 really designed for Netflix=E2=80=99s core product (thus the technical cha=
llenges). What they are is a moment in time where you have FOMO for missing=
 out on a cultural event, and once you sign up to participate, well, now it=
=E2=80=99s a churn mitigation problem, which is exactly what Netflix is bui=
lt for.

Accounting for Events
---------------------

To that end =E2=80=94 and to re-establish my nerdy credentials after talkin=
g about boxing =E2=80=94 I would like it if Netflix classified the cost of =
this content according to its purpose. If I had my druthers, all of the mon=
ey the service is spending on events of this nature should go into marketin=
g, not content, and it should hit the income statement immediately. After a=
ll, it=E2=80=99s not like anyone is going to go back and watch this fight y=
ears into the future; it=E2=80=99s going to be pretty silly to amortize the=
 costs over an extended period.

For what it=E2=80=99s worth, I do not expect Netflix to classify the costs =
in this way =E2=80=94 and to be sure, most viewers were almost certainly ex=
isting Netflix subscribers =E2=80=94 but at a minimum I would expect manage=
ment to exercise its discretion in terms of amortization. From Netflix=E2=
=80=99s 10-K ( https://d18rn0p25nwr6d.cloudfront.net/CIK-0001065280/c5e6498=
2-659f-4726-97c9-c57767c3bec3.pdf ) :

Based on factors including historical and estimated viewing patterns, we am=
ortize the content assets (licensed and produced) in =E2=80=9CCost of reven=
ues=E2=80=9D on the Consolidated Statements of Operations over the shorter =
of each title=E2=80=99s contractual window of availability or estimated per=
iod of use or ten years, beginning with the month of first availability. Th=
e amortization is on an accelerated basis, as we typically expect more upfr=
ont viewing, and film amortization is more accelerated than TV series amort=
ization. On average, over 90% of a licensed or produced content asset is ex=
pected to be amortized within four years after its month of first availabil=
ity. We review factors that impact the amortization of the content assets o=
n a regular basis. Our estimates related to these factors require considera=
ble management judgment.

For now, it=E2=80=99s enough to note the management judgment in realizing d=
ifferent business needs =E2=80=94 customer acquisition and churn mitigation=
 =E2=80=94 do in fact require different strategies. And oh yeah, if you can=
 build up an advertising business along the way, all the better.

